<h1 class="rm-manual">N. Korea bolsters combat readiness of elite military unit</h1>
<p>Sources report that training regimen of the Storm Corps has become more intense this year</p>
<p class="rm-manual">By</p>
<p class="rm-manual"><a href="https://www.dailynk.com/english/author/jong-tae-ju/">Jeong Tae Joo</a></p>
<p class="rm-manual"> - </p>
<p class="rm-manual"><span>2019.12.17 4:00pm</span> </p>
<figcaption>North Korean leader Kim Jong Un observing Storm Corps training in 2013. / Image: Rodong Shinmun</figcaption><p><span>On
 Dec. 7, a special education session was reportedly provided to the 
“Storm Corps,” an elite military unit tasked with the infiltration of 
South Korea as well as sabotage operations during warfare. According to 
sources, the session contained anti-American propaganda claiming “US 
imperialists” were trying to eliminate North Korea’s leader Kim Jong Un.
 </span></p>
<p><span>On Monday, North Korean military sources informed Daily NK 
about a solemn education session held on Saturday at the Storm Corps 
command facilities in Tokchon, South Pyongan Province. The event is said
 to have been supervised by the General Political Bureau’s Propaganda 
and Agitation Department. It might have been an attempt to instill a 
“war-time atmosphere” in the elite military unit. </span></p>
<p><span>A source told Daily NK the session was based on U.S. President 
Donald Trump’s recent threats to order military strikes against North 
Korea. “The speaker condemned [the US] for ‘brazenly discussing regime 
change and precision strikes’, as well as for its ‘unacceptable and 
frenzied efforts to eliminate the leadership’”’ he said.</span></p>
<p><span>“The speaker did not forget to mention that ‘we need to 
actively resist the US imperialists murderous and villainous special 
forces, which have crept into the southern part of the Republic [South 
Korea],’” the source recalled.</span></p>
<p><span>This aligns with the official response of Pak Jong Chon, chief 
of the General Staff of the Korean People’s Army (KPA), to Trump’s 
comments. He had warned that North Korea would retaliate against any US 
attack. </span></p>
<p><span>PREPARING FOR THE WORST? </span></p>
<p><span>North Korea’s Storm Corps unit was founded for the purpose of 
establishing a “second front” across the Korean Peninsula in case of a 
war. The elite military unit is also tasked with political subversion 
operations such as espionage and military sabotage.</span></p>
<p><span>The unit reportedly consists of approximately 20,000 members. 
Its soldiers are said to run an offensive program specifically designed 
for warfare. To prepare for their special operations, the unit’s 
soldiers receive intensive training in both educative and combative.</span></p>
<p><span>“[North Korea] is apparently intensifying class-conscious and 
anti-American education in the Storm Corps, which is known to conduct 
the most brutal special training to prepare for their missions,” a 
source said. “Because the North Korean-American talks are not 
progressing and disparaging comments were made about Kim Jong Un,” he 
said, the country’s leaders have “set out to ramp up education efforts 
in special ops units.”</span></p>
<figcaption>North Korean leader Kim Jong Un and US President Donald 
Trump in Panmunjom on June 30, 2019. The two leaders have not met 
face-to-face since. / Image: Rodong Sinmun</figcaption><p><span>In 
addition, the elite military unit’s combat training has allegedly gotten
 more intense compared to last year: “Soldiers had to endure a 40 
kilometer march in full gear immediately after a battalion’s routine 
inspection of emergency wartime supplies,” the source told Daily NK. 
“High-level officials closely monitored whether all soldiers could 
complete the exercise in time and without any dropouts.”</span></p>
<p><span>“Both the command and the entire battalion had to do the march 
this time whereas previously, fewer personnel had to participate in 
exercises,” the source added. The atmosphere during the exercise, he 
said, was thus “overflowing with tension.”</span></p>
